         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head><p>
               <note>a</note> Hippomedon</p><p>
               <note>b</note> Hippomedon, who was formerly Karpophoros who had nine fights. Nine fights.</p></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>The figure is described by Ghislanzoni, Robert and Brinkerhoff in Kraeling 187, 207, n.71 as a Samnite, but for the rejection of this term, see Robert, p.65. </p>
            <p> The nine palm branches stand for the nine victories mentioned in lines 2-3. </p>
            <p>b.1.  See <ref type="inscription">P31000</ref>. The “stage-name” here, being that of an epic hero, is of a type favoured by gladiators, Robert p. 299. </p>
            <p>b.2, 3.  πυγμαί θ' means  he fought nine battles; for the use of this term for gladiatorial fights, Robert, p. 16f.</p>
         </div>
         
